24~<.\" %W% %G%
.TH Dscale2 2D D-language
.SH NAME
Dscale2 \- Adds a map scale to 
.XT "a map displayed in"
the current 
.CT window "display window"
with options for placing the scale at a UTM coordinate
or with the mouse
.br
.I (D Language Tool)
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B Dscale2
[\fIcolor1\fR [\fIcolor2\fR [\fIeasting\fR \fInorthing\fR [\fI1/0\fR]]]]
.br
.B Dscale2
[option\*=\fIvalue\fR] [option\*=\fIvalue\fR]...
.SH DESCRIPTION
.I Dscale2
displays a scale and North arrow in the current 
.CT "window." "display window."
It is
automatically proportioned to fit appropriately in the upper left corner
of the current 
.CT "window." "display window."
But it can also be position by UTM coordinates or with the mouse.
If you change the position of the scale it may not all fit in the
display window.
It is drawn twice in two different colors; the default
(if unspecified on the command line) is the use of a white scale on a
black background.  Options are:
.ns
.TP 
.RI color1\*= color
Color used for the first drawing of the scale (background).  Default is black.
.br
.ns
.TP 
.RI color2\*= color
Color used for second drawing of the scale (offset).  Default is white.
.PP
Available colors are red, orange, yellow, green, blue, indigo, violet,
gray, brown, magenta, white, and black.  Background and offset colors
can be stated either positionally or explicitly on the command line.
.ns
.TP
.RI easting\*= east-value
Value used for the geographic easting of the upper left corner of the scale.
.br
.ns
.TP
.RI northing\*= north-value
Value used for the geographic northing of the upper left corner of the scale.
.br
.ns
.TP
.RI mouse\*= [1/0]
A 1 indicates that the scale should be placed interactively with the mouse.
A 0 (default) indicates that the mouse not be used.
.br
.SH BUGS
.I Dscale2
assumes that units are in meters.
.br
The scale that \fIDscale\fR generates is not suitable for very tiny maps.
.SH "SEE ALSO"
.TS
ll.
\fIDINTRO[2D]\fR	Introduction to the GRASS \fID\fR tools
.br
\fIDlegend[2D]\fR	T{
Draws a map legend in the current 
.CT window "display window"
T}
.TE
